@kadeng Thanks for you contribution.
Please first make a PR to mshadow and when that's merged, make a PR to mxnet.
This is our standard protocol when working on multiple repos

@javelinjs @kelly-lxg , 

for making mxnet run in one stage, you have to call mxnet within a spark task and block the thread until the training done....e.g. trainingData.mapPartition( partition => mxnet.train ...).foreachPartition(() => _) (each partition maps to a task )

for memory cost, I think we have to accept the overhead in off-heap memory part, unless you rely on 3rd-party solutions to share the memory space between JVM and c++ process (e.g. [Apache Arrow](http://arrow.apache.org/)

@Jordan20160310 I am looking at a very similar setup, but but have prepared .rec with all 1000 classes. I can roughly confirm your numbers of your question 1. I dont have an answer for you at the moment, but will let you know when I find some as I am finding your observation also strange.

Can I ask you the following questions since I am having trouble to continue learning pre-trained models such as inception-bn (https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/issues/1439): Are you starting learning from scratch or continue learning pre-trained inception-bn model from model gallery? In case of the latter what accuracy are you getting right after training start? And are you using train_imagenet.py or some scripts of your own?

In my case learning is always starting from scratch although I am providing pre-trained inception model from model gallery when using train_imagenet.py (and also when doing model = mx.model.FeedForward.load(...) and later model.fit(...) after specifying parameters).
